# Post-change rebuild and refresh (mandatory)

**This rule is mandatory. You must perform these steps every time. Do not skip, summarize, or defer to the user.**

After **any user-facing change** (including features, bug fixes, copy changes, and UI tweaks), before saying the work is "done" or "complete":

## 1. Update build info so this change produces a new build

- Edit **`version.json`**: add a new entry to the **`updates`** array with a short, plain-English description of what changed (e.g. "Removed the word Build from the main menu section.", "Fixed login button on mobile.", "Added Duplicate/Delete to blob menu.").
- Do this for **every user-facing change**, including small copy or UI tweaks. This causes the next build to be treated as a new build and keeps the build tooltip (main menu) accurate.

## 2. Run runapp (new build + dev server)

- In the project root, run: **`npm run runapp`**
- This runs a full build (including writing build-info from `version.json`) and either reuses the existing dev server on port 3000/3001 or starts one if none is running.
- Wait for the command to finish. If it printed "Dev server starting.", wait 2–3 seconds for the server to be ready.

## 3. List Cursor Browser tabs

- Call the **cursor-ide-browser** MCP tool **`browser_tabs`** with **`action: "list"`** to get open tabs and their URLs.

## 4. Refresh the app tab so the existing Cursor Browser shows the update

- If any tab's URL is the app (`http://localhost:3000` or `http://localhost:3001`, with or without path): call **`browser_navigate`** with that same URL plus a **cache-busting query param** (e.g. `http://localhost:3001/?_=1734567890123` using `Date.now()` or a short timestamp). This forces a full reload so the app and build tooltip show the latest build **without the user doing anything**.
- If no tab is on the app: call **`browser_navigate`** with `http://localhost:3000?_=...` (or 3001 if 3000 is in use). Prefer reusing an existing tab; do not ask the user to open the URL.

## When this applies

- After **any user-facing change**: feature, bug fix, copy edit, UI tweak, or config change that affects what the user sees or how the app behaves.
- Before you say the work is "done," "complete," or "ready."

## Hardening

- **Every user-facing change** triggers this flow; no exceptions. Perform all steps as part of closing out the task.
- Do not assume the user will run runapp or refresh the browser. The agent must run runapp and refresh the app tab so the Cursor Browser **automatically** shows the update.
- Do not skip the browser steps because "the user can refresh" or "the build succeeded."
- If the build fails, fix the build (and fix or revert `version.json` if needed), then run runapp again and perform the browser refresh.
- Always use a cache-busting query param on the refresh URL so the loaded page reflects the new build.
